<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia californica </i>is a short-lived shrub that lives to 30 years. It leafs out and flowers whenever moisture is available, usually in spring and lasting sometimes through the fall. Its leaves drop in drought conditions. Its composite heads have showy yellow disk flowers and dark ray flowers <i>. E. californica </i>reproduces by seed and weakly sprouts from damaged stems. It is allelopathic to several winter annual species. <br/>
 <br/>
<i>Eriogonum cinereum </i>(a CNPS list 4 plant) is a much-branched perennial shrub < 1 m tall with white-wooly herbage and white to pinkish flowers. It is endemic to the Venturan coastal scrub region (Axelrod 1978, Malanson 1984, Westman 1981b), with the alliance distribution mainly in the Santa Monica Mountains. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is one of the several alliances of coastal sage scrub (Rundel 2007). Previously in 2009, two separate alliances were defined by the indicator species, which have now been merged into a combined alliance (Rodriguez et al. 2017). Stands of both <i>Encelia californica </i> and <i>E. cinereum </i>are characteristic of relatively steep slopes and cliffs, and the species occur in many other coastal sage scrub types, including the <i>Artemisia californica, Malosma laurina, Rhus integrifolia, Salvia leucophylla, </i>and <i>Salvia mellifera </i>alliances. Despite its preference for sunny steep exposures, the alliance is usually associated with some summer fog and usually exists close to the coast (Kirkpatrick and Hutchinson 1980, Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). A post-fire phase of the alliance may have high cover of <i>Leymus condensatus </i>and <i>Malacothamnus fasciculatus</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
