<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Post-fire studies of the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeley and Keeley 1984, O’Leary 1990) found <i>Encelia californica </i>vigorously sprouted from the shrub’s main shoot and the sprouts produced flowers and set seed within the second year after fire, with seedlings successfully establishing as well. <i>Eriogonum cinereum </i>can also vigorous sprout from the root crown after fire, especially in less intense fires (Westman 1981a, Keeley and Keeley 1984). Seeds typically do not germinate from the seed bank. Instead, the sprouting shrubs flower and set seed in the year after a fire. Seedlings appear in the second season.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (15-70+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
