</div>



    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-j). Stands from the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), and generally for the section (Kirkpatrick and Hutchinson 1977, Malanson 1984) vary greatly in species composition. Stands with <i>Encelia californica </i>are rare on Santa Cruz Island and are likely to occur on south-facing slopes on San Clemente.  Stands have been sampled on Anacapa and Santa Catalina islands (Rodriguez et al. 2017, Dixon et al. 2019). Stands with <i>Encelia californica </i>are common at Cabrillo National Monument in disturbed areas and associate with <i>Euphorbia misera </i>on rocky southerly exposures. Stands with <i>Eriogonum cinereum </i>are more restricted than <i>Encelia californica</i> in that they occur to the Los Angeles basin and hills near Newport Beach and not further south.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bj-k). Stands with <i>Encelia californica </i> and <i>Artemisia californica </i>from the western subsections exist no more than about 50 km from the coast (Evens and San 2005, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Increased urbanization, especially in the South Coast, and non-native invasive plants are impacting the range of this alliance. <i>Encelia californica </i>rapidly colonizes roadsides and other disturbed areas, but repeated fires at less than 10-year intervals negatively impact stands by increasing the abundance of non-native species. By virtue of their ability to colonize and dominate steep unstable slopes, managers could use both <i>E. californica </i> and<i>Eriogonum cinereum </i> for erosion control. </div>
</div>

    

    

